{
  "What is torque?": "",
  "A twisting force that causes rotation around a pivot point": "",
  "A force that pushes an object in a straight line forward": "",
  "The speed at which an object moves along a straight path": "",
  "The weight of an object measured in kilograms of mass": "",
  "Torque is a twisting force that causes or tends to cause rotation around a pivot point (fulcrum). It depends on both the force applied and the distance from the pivot.": "",
  "What two factors determine the amount of torque?": "",
  "Mass and volume of the rotating object": "",
  "Force applied and distance from the pivot": "",
  "Temperature and pressure of the environment": "",
  "Color and shape of the rotating object here": "",
  "Torque = force x distance from pivot. A larger force or a greater distance from the pivot produces more torque. This is why using a longer wrench makes turning a bolt easier.": "",
  "What is the formula for torque?": "",
  "Torque = mass x acceleration": "",
  "Torque = force x velocity": "",
  "Torque = force x lever arm distance": "",
  "Torque = mass x distance traveled": "",
  "Torque equals the force multiplied by the lever arm (perpendicular distance from the force to the pivot point). Torque is measured in newton-meters (N-m).": "",
  "What is the pivot point also called?": "",
  "The fulcrum of the rotating system": "",
  "The weight of the rotating object": "",
  "The velocity of the rotation spin": "",
  "The mass of the rotating body here": "",
  "The pivot point is also called the fulcrum. It is the fixed point around which an object rotates. A seesaw rotates around its fulcrum in the middle.": "",
  "Why does a longer wrench make it easier to turn a bolt?": "",
  "It provides a greater distance from the pivot, increasing torque": "",
  "It makes the bolt lighter so it turns more easily and freely": "",
  "It decreases friction between the wrench and the bolt surfaces": "",
  "It applies less force to the bolt making it rotate more easily": "",
  "A longer wrench increases the lever arm distance. Since torque = force x distance, a greater distance means more torque with the same force. This makes turning the bolt easier.": "",
  "What unit is torque measured in?": "",
  "Kilograms per meter": "",
  "Meters per second squared": "",
  "Newton-meters (N-m)": "",
  "Watts per second value": "",
  "Torque is measured in newton-meters (N-m), since it equals force (newtons) multiplied by distance (meters). This is different from joules, even though both are N-m, because torque involves rotation.": "",
  "If you push on a door near the hinge, is it easy or hard to open?": "",
  "Easy, because you are close to the pivot point": "",
  "Hard, because the lever arm distance is very small": "",
  "Easy, because less force is needed close to the hinge": "",
  "Hard, because the door gets heavier near the hinge": "",
  "Pushing near the hinge means a very small lever arm distance, which produces little torque. You would need a very large force to open the door. This is why door handles are placed far from the hinge.": "",
  "What is rotational motion?": "",
  "Motion where an object spins around an axis or pivot point": "",
  "Motion where an object moves in a straight line forward": "",
  "Motion where an object moves up and down repeatedly": "",
  "Motion where an object stays perfectly still at all times": "",
  "Rotational motion is when an object spins or rotates around a fixed axis or pivot point. Examples include a spinning top, a turning wheel, and Earth rotating on its axis.": "",
  "On a balanced seesaw, what is true about the torques on each side?": "",
  "The torques are equal and opposite for balance": "",
  "The heavier side always has less torque value": "",
  "Only one side produces any torque on the seesaw": "",
  "The torques are unrelated to the balance of it": "",
  "For a seesaw to balance, the clockwise torque must equal the counterclockwise torque. This means force x distance on one side equals force x distance on the other side.": "",
  "A force of 20 N is applied 0.5 m from a pivot. What is the torque?": "",
  "40 newton-meters of torque": "",
  "10 newton-meters of torque": "",
  "0.025 newton-meters of torque": "",
  "20.5 newton-meters of torque": "",
  "Torque = force x distance = 20 N x 0.5 m = 10 N-m. The torque is 10 newton-meters about the pivot point.": "",
  "The measure of a force's ability to cause rotation": "",
  "The speed at which an object moves along a path": "",
  "The total mass of a rotating object on an axis": "",
  "The energy stored in a spinning wheel or flywheel": "",
  "Torque is the measure of a force's ability to cause rotation around a pivot. It depends on the force magnitude and the perpendicular distance from the pivot (lever arm).": "",
  "What does 'lever arm' mean?": "",
  "The perpendicular distance from the pivot to the force": "",
  "The total length of the rotating object or beam here": "",
  "The force applied to make an object rotate around": "",
  "The mass of the arm of a person pushing the lever": "",
  "The lever arm is the perpendicular distance from the line of action of the force to the pivot point. A longer lever arm produces more torque for the same force.": "",
  "What does 'fulcrum' mean?": "",
  "The fixed pivot point around which rotation occurs": "",
  "The speed of rotation measured in revolutions": "",
  "The mass of the object that is being rotated": "",
  "The fulcrum is the fixed point around which a lever or object rotates. On a seesaw, the fulcrum is the central support. On a door, the hinges act as the fulcrum.": "",
  "What does 'clockwise' mean in the context of torque?": "",
  "Rotation in the same direction as clock hands move": "",
  "Rotation opposite to the direction clock hands move": "",
  "Rotation that does not involve any torque at all": "",
  "A type of force that prevents rotation from occurring": "",
  "Clockwise rotation is in the same direction clock hands move (from 12 to 3 to 6 to 9). In torque problems, clockwise and counterclockwise torques are considered in opposite directions.": "",
  "What does 'counterclockwise' mean?": "",
  "Rotation in the direction clock hands move forward": "",
  "A force applied directly at the pivot point itself": "",
  "No rotation occurring in any direction at all here": "",
  "Counterclockwise rotation is opposite to the direction clock hands move (from 12 to 9 to 6 to 3). When torques in both directions are equal, the object is in rotational equilibrium.": "",
  "What does 'rotational equilibrium' mean?": "",
  "When clockwise and counterclockwise torques are equal": "",
  "When an object spins faster and faster over time here": "",
  "When no forces act on the object at all in any way": "",
  "When the object moves in a straight line with no spin": "",
  "Rotational equilibrium occurs when the total clockwise torque equals the total counterclockwise torque. The net torque is zero, so the object does not rotate or rotates at constant angular velocity.": "",
  "What is meant by 'axis of rotation'?": "",
  "The imaginary line around which an object rotates": "",
  "The force that causes the object to start rotating": "",
  "The speed at which the object completes one turn": "",
  "The weight of the object that is rotating around": "",
  "The axis of rotation is the imaginary line around which an object spins. For a wheel, it is the axle. For Earth, it is the line from North Pole to South Pole.": "",
  "What does 'moment of force' mean?": "",
  "Another term for torque in physics calculations": "",
  "The instant when a force first begins to act": "",
  "The momentum of an object moving in a circle": "",
  "The time it takes for one complete rotation cycle": "",
  "Moment of force is another term for torque. It refers to the turning effect of a force about a pivot point. Moment = force x perpendicular distance from the pivot.": "",
  "What does 'angular velocity' mean?": "",
  "The rate at which an object rotates, measured in turns per time": "",
  "The speed at which an object moves in a straight line forward": "",
  "The distance from the center of rotation to the outer edge": "",
  "The mass of an object that is spinning around an axis": "",
  "Angular velocity is the rate of rotation, describing how fast an object spins. It can be measured in revolutions per second, degrees per second, or radians per second.": "",
  "What does 'perpendicular' mean when applying force for torque?": "",
  "At a 90-degree angle to the lever arm for maximum torque": "",
  "Parallel to the lever arm for maximum possible torque": "",
  "Directly at the pivot point for maximum torque value": "",
  "In the same direction as the rotation of the object": "",
  "Perpendicular means at a 90-degree angle. Torque is maximized when the force is applied perpendicular to the lever arm. Pushing at an angle less than 90 degrees reduces the effective torque.": "",
  "A child weighing 300 N sits 2 m from the fulcrum of a seesaw. What torque do they produce?": "",
